p5-Encode-HanExtra.name: p5-Encode-HanExtra
p5-Encode-HanExtra.desc:
Perl 5.7.3 and later ships with an adequate set of Chinese encodings,
including the commonly used CP950, CP936 (also known as GBK), Big5
(alias for Big5-Eten), Big5-HKSCS, EUC-CN, HZ, and ISO-IR-165.

However, the numbers of Chinese encodings are staggering, and a complete
coverage will easily increase the size of perl distribution by several
megabytes; hence, this CPAN module tries to provide the rest of them.

If you are using perl 5.8 or later, Encode::CN and Encode::TW will
automatically load the extra encodings for you, so there's no need to
explicitly write use Encode::HanExtra if you are using one of them already.

p5-Encode-JIS2K.name: p5-Encode-JIS2K
p5-Encode-JIS2K.desc:
This module implements encodings that covers JIS X 0213 charset (AKA
JIS 2000, hence the module name). Encodings supported are as follows.

Canonical     Alias                                      Description
--------------------------------------------------------------------
euc-jisx0213  qr/\beuc.*jp[ \-]?(?:2000|2k)$/i          EUC-JISX0213
              qr/\bjp.*euc[ \-]?(2000|2k)$/i
              qr/\bujis[ \-]?(?:2000|2k)$/i
shiftjisx0123 qr/\bshift.*jis(?:2000|2k)$/i           Shift_JISX0213
              qr/\bsjisp \-]?(?:2000|2k)$/i

iso-2022-jp-3
jis0213-1-raw                         JIS X 0213 plane 1, raw format
jis0213-2-raw                         JIS X 0213 plane 2, raw format

p5-Error.name: p5-Error
p5-Error.comment: Error/exception handling in object-oriented programming style
p5-Error.desc:
The Error package provides two interfaces. Firstly Error provides a procedural
interface to exception handling. Secondly Error is a base class for
errors/exceptions that can either be thrown, for subsequent catch, or can simply
be recorded.

Errors in the class Error should not be thrown directly, but the user should
throw errors from a sub-class of Error.

p5-File-HomeDir.name: p5-File-HomeDir
p5-File-HomeDir.comment: Get home directory for self or other users
p5-File-HomeDir.desc:
File::HomeDir -- get home directory for self or other users

This module provides a function, home, and also ties the in-all-packages
variable %25~.

p5-File-Which.name: p5-File-Which
p5-File-Which.comment: Portable implementation of which(1) in Perl
p5-File-Which.desc:
File::Which is a portable implementation (in Perl) of `which', and can
be used to get the absolute filename of an executable program
installed somewhere in your PATH, or just check for its existence.

p5-GSSAPI.name: p5-GSSAPI
p5-GSSAPI.comment: Perl extension providing access to the GSSAPIv2 library
p5-GSSAPI.desc:
This module gives access to the routines of the GSSAPI library,
as described in rfc2743 and rfc2744 and implemented by the
Kerberos-1.2 distribution from MIT.

p5-HTML-Parser.name: p5-HTML-Parser
p5-HTML-Parser.comment: Perl5 module for parsing HTML documents
p5-HTML-Parser.desc:
This is a collection of modules that parse HTML text documents. These
modules used to be part of the libwww-perl distribution, but are now
unbundled in order to facilitate a separate development track.  Bug
reports and discussions about these modules can still be sent to the
<libwww-perl@ics.uci.edu> mailing list.  Remember to also take a look at
the HTML-Tree module collection that create and extract information from
HTML syntax trees.

p5-HTML-Tagset.name: p5-HTML-Tagset
p5-HTML-Tagset.comment: Some useful data table in parsing HTML
p5-HTML-Tagset.desc:
This module contains several data tables useful in various kinds of
HTML parsing operations.

Note that all tag names used are lowercase.

In the following documentation, a "hashset" is a hash being used as a
set -- the hash conveys that its keys are there, and the actual values
associated with the keys are not significant.  (But what values are
there, are always true.)

p5-HTTP-Date.name: p5-HTTP-Date
p5-HTTP-Date.comment: Conversion routines for the HTTP protocol date formats
p5-HTTP-Date.desc:
HTTP::Date provides functions that deal the date formats used by the HTTP
protocol (and then some more). Only the first two functions, time2str() and
str2time(), are exported by default.

p5-HTTP-Message.name: p5-HTTP-Message
p5-HTTP-Message.desc:
This module contains classes useful for representing the messages passed
in HTTP style communication. These are classes representing requests,
responses and the headers contained within them.

p5-IO-HTML.name: p5-IO-HTML
p5-IO-HTML.comment: Open an HTML file with automatic charset detection
p5-IO-HTML.desc:
IO::HTML provides an easy way to open a file containing HTML while
automatically determining its encoding. It uses the HTML5 encoding
sniffing algorithm specified in section 8.2.2.1 of the draft standard.

p5-IO-Socket-IP.name: p5-IO-Socket-IP
p5-IO-Socket-IP.comment: Drop-in replacement for IO::Socket::INET supporting IPv4 and IPv6
p5-IO-Socket-IP.desc:
IO::Socket::IP provides a protocol-independent way to use IPv4 and IPv6 sockets,
as a drop-in replacement for IO::Socket::INET. Most constructor arguments and
methods are provided in a backward-compatible way. For a list of known
differences, see the IO::Socket::INET INCOMPATIBILITES section below.

It uses the getaddrinfo(3) function to convert hostnames and service names or
port numbers into sets of possible addresses to connect to or listen on. This
allows it to work for IPv6 where the system supports it, while still falling
back to IPv4-only on systems which don't.

p5-IO-Socket-SSL.name: p5-IO-Socket-SSL
p5-IO-Socket-SSL.desc:
IO::Socket::SSL is a class implementing an object oriented
interface to SSL sockets. The class is a descendent of
IO::Socket::INET and provides a subset of the base class's
interface methods.

p5-IO-Tty.name: p5-IO-Tty
p5-IO-Tty.comment: Flexible I/O Perl5 module that allows manipulation of pseudo-TTYs
p5-IO-Tty.desc:
Perl5 module that allows creation of pseudo-tty's
as well as manipulation.

p5-IPC-Run.name: p5-IPC-Run
p5-IPC-Run.comment: Run subprocesses with piping and redirection
p5-IPC-Run.desc:
IPC::Run allows you run and interact with child processes, files, pipes,
and pseudo-ttys.  Both event-loop and procedural techniques are
supported and may be mixed.  Likewise, functional and OO API styles are
both supported and may be mixed.

p5-JSON.name: p5-JSON
p5-JSON.comment: Perl extension to convert to JSON (JavaScript Object Notation)
p5-JSON.desc: Perl extension interface to convert to JSON (JavaScript Object Notation).

p5-JSON-XS.name: p5-JSON-XS
p5-JSON-XS.comment: JSON serialising/deserialising, done correctly and fast
p5-JSON-XS.desc:
This module converts Perl data structures to JSON and vice versa.
Its primary goal is to be correct and its secondary goal is to be fast.
To reach the latter goal it was written in C.

As this is the n-th-something JSON module on CPAN, what was the reason
to write yet another JSON module? While it seems there are many JSON
modules, none of them correctly handle all corner cases, and in most
cases their maintainers are unresponsive, gone missing, or not listening
to bug reports for other reasons.

p5-Locale-gettext.name: p5-Locale-gettext
p5-Locale-gettext.desc:
This module permits from perl to the gettext() family of functions
for retrieving message strings from databases constructed to
internationalize software.

p5-Locale-libintl.name: p5-Locale-libintl
p5-Locale-libintl.desc:
The package libintl-perl is an internationalization library for Perl
that aims to be compatible with the Uniforum message translations
system as implemented for example in GNU gettext.

p5-LWP-MediaTypes.name: p5-LWP-MediaTypes
p5-LWP-MediaTypes.comment: Guess media type for a file or a URL
p5-LWP-MediaTypes.desc:
LWP::MediaTypes provides functions for handling media (also known as MIME) types
and encodings. The mapping from file extensions to media types is defined by the
media.types file. If the ~/.media.types file exists it is used instead. For
backwards compatibility we will also look for ~/.mime.types.

p5-Module-Build.name: p5-Module-Build
p5-Module-Build.desc:
Module::Build is a system for building, testing, and installing Perl modules.
It is meant to be a replacement for ExtUtils::MakeMaker. Developers may alter
the behavior of the module through subclassing in a much more straightforward
way than with MakeMaker. It also does not require a make on your system - most
of the Module::Build code is pure-perl and written in a very cross-platform
way.

p5-Mozilla-CA.name: p5-Mozilla-CA
p5-Mozilla-CA.comment: Perl extension for Mozilla CA cert bundle in PEM format
p5-Mozilla-CA.desc:
Mozilla::CA provides a copy of Mozilla's bundle of Certificate
Authority certificates in a form that can be consumed by modules and
libraries based on OpenSSL.

p5-Net-SSLeay.name: p5-Net-SSLeay
p5-Net-SSLeay.desc:
This module offers

- some high level convenience functions for accessing web pages on SSL servers
- a sslcat() function for writing your own clients
- access to the SSL api of SSLeay package,
  so you can write servers or clients for more complicated applications

p5-Parse-Yapp.name: p5-Parse-Yapp
p5-Parse-Yapp.comment: Perl extension for generating and using LALR parsers
p5-Parse-Yapp.desc:
Parse::Yapp lets you create Perl OO fully reentrant LALR(1) parser modules
and has been designed to be functionally as close as possible to yacc,
but using the full power of Perl and opened for enhancements.

p5-Text-Unidecode.name: p5-Text-Unidecode
p5-Text-Unidecode.desc:
It often happens that you have non-Roman text data in Unicode, but you
can't display it -- usually because you're trying to show it to a user
via an application that doesn't support Unicode, or because the fonts
you need aren't accessible.  You could represent the Unicode characters
as "???????" or "\15BA\15A0\1610...", but that's nearly useless to the
user who actually wants to read what the text says.

What Text::Unidecode provides is a function, unidecode(...) that takes
Unicode data and tries to represent it in US-ASCII characters.

p5-TimeDate.name: p5-TimeDate
p5-TimeDate.comment: Perl5 module containing a better/faster date parser for absolute dates
p5-TimeDate.desc:
The TimeDate distribution replaces earlier GetDate distribution, which was
only a date parser. The date parser contained in this distribution
is far superior to the yacc based parser, and a *lot* faster.

The parser contained here will only parse absolute dates, if you want a date
parser that can parse relative dates then take a look at the
Time modules by David Muir on CPAN.

The file Local.pm.new which is included in this distribution is a patched
version of Time::Local which comes with perl. It fixes two problems

    - It determines the zone offset based on now rather than epoch
    - It fixes a problem with looping forever when a year > 1900 is passed in

p5-Try-Tiny.name: p5-Try-Tiny
p5-Try-Tiny.comment: Minimal try/catch with proper localization of $@
p5-Try-Tiny.desc:
This module provides bare bones try/catch statements that are designed
to minimize common mistakes done with eval blocks (for instance assuming
that $@ is set to a true value on error, or clobbering previous values
of $@, and NOTHING else.

p5-Types-Serialiser.name: p5-Types-Serialiser
p5-Types-Serialiser.comment: Simple data types for common serialisation formats
p5-Types-Serialiser.desc:
Types::Serialiser provides some extra datatypes that are used by common
serialisation formats such as JSON or CBOR. The idea is to have a repository of
simple/small constants and containers that can be shared by different
implementations so they become interoperable between each other.

p5-Unicode-EastAsianWidth.name: p5-Unicode-EastAsianWidth
p5-Unicode-EastAsianWidth.desc:
Unicode::EastAsianWidth provide user-defined Unicode properties that deal with
width status of East Asian characters, as specified in
http://www.unicode.org/unicode/reports/tr11/.

It exports the following functions to the caller's scope, to be used by Perl's
Unicode matching system: InEastAsianFullwidth, InEastAsianHalfwidth,
InEastAsianAmbiguous, InEastAsianNarrow InEastAsianWide, InEastAsianNeutral.

In accord to TR11 cited above, two additional context-sensitive properties are
exported: InFullwidth (union of Fullwidth and Wide) and InHalfwidth (union of
Halfwidth, Narrow and Neutral).

Ambiguous characters are treated by default as part of InHalfwidth, but you can
modify this behaviour by assigning a true value to
$Unicode::EastAsianWidth::EastAsian at compile time within a BEGIN block before
loading this module

p5-URI.name: p5-URI
p5-URI.comment: Perl5 interface to Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) references
p5-URI.desc:
This package contains the URI.pm module with friends.  The module
implements the URI class.  Objects of this class represent Uniform
Resource Identifier (URI) references as specified in RFC 2396 and
updated by RFC 2732.  Release 1.50 includes the initial attempt at
providing support to IRIs.  URI objects now support the 'as_iri'
and 'ihost' methods.

URI objects can be used to access and manipulate the various
components that make up these strings.  There are also methods to
combine URIs in various ways.

The URI class replaces the URI::URL class that used to be distributed
with libwww-perl.  This package contains an emulation of the old
URI::URL interface.  The emulated URI::URL implements both the old and
the new interface.

p5-XML-Parser.name: p5-XML-Parser
p5-XML-Parser.comment: Perl extension interface to James Clark's XML parser, expat
p5-XML-Parser.desc: Perl extension interface to James Clark's XML parser, expat.

p5-YAML-Tiny.name: p5-YAML-Tiny
p5-YAML-Tiny.comment: Read/Write YAML files with as little code as possible
p5-YAML-Tiny.desc:
YAML::Tiny is a perl class to read and write YAML-style files with as
little code as possible, reducing load time and memory overhead.

PackageKit.name: PackageKit
PackageKit.desc:
PackageKit is a DBUS abstraction layer that allows the session user to manage
packages in a secure way using a cross-distro, cross-architecture API.

PackageKit-Qt5.name: PackageKit-Qt5
PackageKit-Qt5.desc:
PackageKit is a DBUS abstraction layer that allows the session user to manage
packages in a secure way using a cross-distro, cross-architecture API. This
library provides Qt-styled API to PackageKit.

pango.name: pango
pango.comment: Open-source framework for the layout and rendering of i18n text
pango.desc:
Pango provides a framework to render and control the layout of
internationalized text, and is the backend for right-to-left text.
Pango is an integral part of the GTK+ and GNOME projects, but its
code is platform- and toolkit-independent.

pcaudiolib.name: pcaudiolib
pcaudiolib.desc:
The Portable C Audio Library (pcaudiolib) provides a C API to different
audio devices. Supported backends are ALSA, OSS, and PulseAudio.

This Port can be built with any combination of the supported backends,
but official packages are distributed with OSS support only, in order
to not depend on the other backends being installed.

pciids.name: pciids
pciids.comment: Database of all known IDs used in PCI devices
pciids.desc: Database of all known ID's used in PCI devices

pcre.name: pcre
pcre.desc:
The PCRE library is a set of functions that implement regular expression
pattern matching using the same syntax and semantics as Perl 5. PCRE has its
own native API, as well as a set of wrapper functions that correspond to the
POSIX regular expression API. The PCRE library is free, even for building
proprietary software.

pcre2.name: pcre2
pcre2.comment: Perl Compatible Regular Expressions library, version 2
pcre2.desc:
PCRE2 is the name used for a revised API for the PCRE library, which is
a set of functions, written in C, that implement regular expression
pattern matching using the same syntax and semantics as Perl, with just
a few differences. Some features that appeared in Python and the
original PCRE before they appeared in Perl are also available using the
Python syntax. There is also some support for one or two .NET and
Oniguruma syntax items, and there are options for requesting some minor
changes that give better ECMAScript (aka JavaScript) compatibility.

perl5.name: perl5
perl5.desc:
Perl is a language that combines some of the features of C, sed, awk and
shell.  See the manual page for more hype.  There are also many books
published by O'Reilly & Assoc.  See pod/perlbook.pod for more
information.

phonon-gstreamer-qt5.name: phonon-gstreamer-qt5
phonon-gstreamer-qt5.desc:
Phonon is the multimedia framework for KDE Software Compilation.
This port provides the GStreamer backend.

messages.message:
You'll need to install some GStreamer plugins to make Phonon able to
play something via this backend: multimedia/gstreamer1-plugins-all
will let you choose among all of them.

phonon-qt5.name: phonon-qt5
phonon-qt5.desc:
Phonon is the framework responsible for an ubiquitous multimedia
experience in KDE Software Compilation 4 and KDe Plasma Desktop.

messages.message:
Please, consider installing backends for Phonon:
- multimedia/phonon-vlc		VLC backend

phonon-vlc-qt5.name: phonon-vlc-qt5
phonon-vlc-qt5.desc:
Phonon is the multimedia framework for KDE Software Compilation.
This port provides the VLC backend.

pinentry.name: pinentry
pinentry.comment: Collection of simple PIN or passphrase entry dialogs
pinentry.desc:
This is a collection of simple PIN or passphrase entry dialogs which
utilize the Assuan protocol as described by the aegypten project.

pinentry-curses.name: pinentry-curses
pinentry-curses.comment: Curses version of the GnuPG password dialog
pinentry-curses.desc:
This is a collection of simple PIN or passphrase entry dialogs which
utilize the Assuan protocol as described by the aegypten project.

pinentry-qt5.name: pinentry-qt5
pinentry-qt5.comment: Qt 5 version of the GnuPG password dialog
pinentry-qt5.desc:
This is a collection of simple PIN or passphrase entry dialogs which
utilize the Assuan protocol as described by the aegypten project.

pipewire.name: pipewire
pipewire.comment: Server and user space API to deal with multimedia pipelines
pipewire.desc:
PipeWire is a server and user space API to deal with multimedia pipelines. This
includes:
- Making available sources of video (such as from a capture devices or
  application provided streams) and multiplexing this with clients.
- Accessing sources of video for consumption.
- Generating graphs for audio and video processing.

pixman.name: pixman
pixman.desc: This package contains the pixman library.

pkcs11-helper.name: pkcs11-helper
pkcs11-helper.comment: Helper library for multiple PKCS#11 providers
pkcs11-helper.desc:
pkcs11-helper is a library that simplifies the interaction
with PKCS#11 providers for end-user applications.

pkcs11-helper allows using multiple PKCS#11 providers at
the same time, enumerating available token certificates, or
selecting a certificate directly by serialized id, handling
card removal and card insert events, handling card re-insert
to a different slot, supporting session expiration and much
more all using a simple API.

pkcs11-helper is not designed to manage card content, since
object attributes are usually vendor specific, and 99%25 of
application need to access existing objects in order to
perform signature and decryption.

pkgconf.name: pkgconf
pkgconf.comment: Utility to help to configure compiler and linker flags
pkgconf.desc:
pkgconf is a program which helps to configure compiler and linker flags for
development frameworks. It is similar to pkg-config, but was written from
scratch in Summer of 2011 to replace pkg-config, which now needs itself to
build itself.

plasma-wayland-protocols.name: plasma-wayland-protocols
plasma-wayland-protocols.desc:
Plasma Wayland Protocols

This project should be installing only the xml files of the non-standard
wayland protocols we use in Plasma.

They are installed to $PREFIX/share/plasma-wayland-protocols.

plasma5-breeze.name: plasma5-breeze
plasma5-breeze.comment: Plasma5 artwork, styles and assets for the Breeze visual style
plasma5-breeze.desc: Artwork, styles and assets for the Breeze visual style for the Plasma Desktop

plasma5-breeze-gtk.name: plasma5-breeze-gtk
plasma5-breeze-gtk.comment: Plasma5 Breeze visual style for Gtk

plasma5-discover.name: plasma5-discover
plasma5-discover.desc: A collection of package management tools for KDE.

plasma5-kactivitymanagerd.name: plasma5-kactivitymanagerd
plasma5-kactivitymanagerd.comment: System service to manage user's activities, track the usage patterns
plasma5-kactivitymanagerd.desc:
KActivities provides the infrastructure needed to manage a user's activites,
allowing them to switch between tasks, and for applications to update their
state to match the user's current activity. This includes a daemon, a library
for interacting with that daemon, and plugins for integration with other
frameworks.

plasma5-kde-cli-tools.name: plasma5-kde-cli-tools
plasma5-kde-cli-tools.desc: Tools based on KDE Frameworks 5 to better interact with the system.

plasma5-kde-gtk-config.name: plasma5-kde-gtk-config
plasma5-kde-gtk-config.desc:
GTK2 and GTK3 Configurator for KDE.

Configuration dialog to adapt GTK applications appearance to your taste under
KDE. Among its many features, it lets you:
* Choose which theme is used for GTK2 and GTK3 applications.
* Tweak some GTK applications behaviour.
* Select what icon theme to use in GTK applications.
* Select GTK applications default fonts.
* Easily browse and install new GTK2 and GTK3 themes.

plasma5-kdecoration.name: plasma5-kdecoration
plasma5-kdecoration.comment: Plasma5 library to create window decorations
plasma5-kdecoration.desc: Plugin based library to create window decorations

plasma5-kdeplasma-addons.name: plasma5-kdeplasma-addons
plasma5-kdeplasma-addons.comment: Plasma5 addons to improve the Plasma experience
plasma5-kdeplasma-addons.desc: All kind of addons to improve your Plasma experience.

plasma5-kinfocenter.name: plasma5-kinfocenter
plasma5-kinfocenter.desc: KInfoCenter is a utility that provides information about a computer system.

plasma5-kpipewire.name: plasma5-kpipewire
plasma5-kpipewire.desc:
Plasma applet for audio volume management using PulseAudio

For users of pulseaudio, this provides extended mixer applet.

plasma5-kscreenlocker.name: plasma5-kscreenlocker
plasma5-kscreenlocker.desc: Library and components for secure lock screen architecture.

plasma5-ksshaskpass.name: plasma5-ksshaskpass
plasma5-ksshaskpass.desc: ssh-add helper that uses kwallet and kpassworddialog.

plasma5-ksysguard.name: plasma5-ksysguard
plasma5-ksysguard.comment: Plasma5 utility to track and control the running processes
plasma5-ksysguard.desc:
KSysGuard, also known as KDE System Guard and KDE System Monitor, is designed
to make simple process control available to a user without needing to do any
special setup - the defaults are usually perfectly adequate. There are two
worksheets - the System Load page, pictured above, and the Process Table.

plasma5-ksystemstats.name: plasma5-ksystemstats
plasma5-ksystemstats.comment: Plasma5 library to report system activity
plasma5-ksystemstats.desc:
KSystemStats is a daemon that collects statistics about the running system.

On FreeBSD, KSystemStats implements low-overhead sysctl-based
monitoring for KDE Plasma applications that report on system resource
usage (e.g. ksysguard and system-monitor and widgets).

plasma5-kwayland-integration.name: plasma5-kwayland-integration
plasma5-kwayland-integration.comment: Integration plugins for a Wayland-based desktop
plasma5-kwayland-integration.desc:
Provides integration plugins for various KDE frameworks for
the wayland windowing system.

plasma5-kwrited.name: plasma5-kwrited
plasma5-kwrited.comment: Plasma5 daemon listening for wall and write messages
plasma5-kwrited.desc: Plasma5 daemon listening for wall and write messages.

plasma5-layer-shell-qt.name: plasma5-layer-shell-qt
plasma5-layer-shell-qt.comment: Qt component to make use of the Wayland wl-layer-shell protoco
plasma5-layer-shell-qt.desc:
This component is meant for applications to be able to easily use clients based
on wlr-layer-shell.  Here you can read about what the protocol does and how
shells work:

https://drewdevault.com/2018/07/29/Wayland-shells.html

plasma5-libksysguard.name: plasma5-libksysguard
plasma5-libksysguard.comment: Plasma5 library to track and control running processes
plasma5-libksysguard.desc: Track and control the processes running in your system.

plasma5-milou.name: plasma5-milou
plasma5-milou.desc: A dedicated search Plasmoid built on top of Baloo.

plasma5-plasma-browser-integration.name: plasma5-plasma-browser-integration
plasma5-plasma-browser-integration.comment: Plasma5 components to integrate browsers into the desktop
plasma5-plasma-browser-integration.desc: Components necessary to integrate browsers into the Plasma Desktop.

plasma5-plasma-desktop.name: plasma5-plasma-desktop
plasma5-plasma-desktop.desc:
Plasma Desktop offers all the tools required for a modern desktop computing
experience so you can be productive right from the start.

plasma5-plasma-disks.name: plasma5-plasma-disks
plasma5-plasma-disks.comment: Monitors S.M.A.R.T. capable devices for imminent failure
plasma5-plasma-disks.desc: Monitors S.M.A.R.T. capable devices for imminent failure.

plasma5-plasma-integration.name: plasma5-plasma-integration
plasma5-plasma-integration.comment: Qt Platform Theme integration plugins for the Plasma workspaces
plasma5-plasma-integration.desc: Qt Platform Theme integration plugins for the Plasma workspaces.

plasma5-plasma-pa.name: plasma5-plasma-pa
plasma5-plasma-pa.desc:
Plasma applet for audio volume management using PulseAudio

For users of pulseaudio, this provides extended mixer applet.

plasma5-plasma-sdk.name: plasma5-plasma-sdk
plasma5-plasma-sdk.comment: Plasma5 applications useful for Plasma development

messages.message:
To start plasma5 via x11/startx add the following to your .xinitrc file:

    exec ck-launch-session startplasma-x11

plasma5-polkit-kde-agent-1.name: plasma5-polkit-kde-agent-1
plasma5-polkit-kde-agent-1.comment: Plasma5 daemon providing a polkit authentication UI
plasma5-polkit-kde-agent-1.desc: Daemon providing a polkit authentication UI for KDE

plasma5-powerdevil.name: plasma5-powerdevil
plasma5-powerdevil.comment: Plasma5 tool to manage the power consumption settings
plasma5-powerdevil.desc: Manages the power consumption settings of a Plasma Shell.

plasma5-xdg-desktop-portal-kde.name: plasma5-xdg-desktop-portal-kde
plasma5-xdg-desktop-portal-kde.desc:
A backend implementation for xdg-desktop-portal that is using Qt/KF5.

xdg-desktop-portal works by exposing a series of D-Bus interfaces known as
portals under a well-known name (org.freedesktop.portal.Desktop) and object
path (/org/freedesktop/portal/desktop).

The portal interfaces include APIs for file access, opening URIs, printing and
others.

png.name: png
png.desc:
Libpng was written as a companion to the PNG specification, as a
way to reduce the amount of time and effort it takes to support
the PNG file format in application programs.  Most users will not
have to modify the library significantly; advanced users may want
to modify it more.  The library was coded for both users.  All
attempts were made to make it as complete as possible, while
keeping the code easy to understand.  Currently, this library
only supports C.  Support for other languages is being considered.

LICENSE: libpng license

     http://libpng.sourceforge.net/

polkit.name: polkit
polkit.comment: Framework for controlling access to system-wide components
polkit.desc:
Polkit is a toolkit for defining and handling authorizations. It is used
for allowing unprivileged processes to speak to privileged processes.

polkit-qt-1.name: polkit-qt-1
polkit-qt-1.desc:
Polkit-Qt is a library that lets developers use the Polkit API through
a nice Qt-styled API. It is mainly a wrapper around QAction and
QAbstractButton that lets you integrate those two component easily
with Polkit.

polkit-qt-1-qt5.name: polkit-qt-1-qt5
polkit-qt-1-qt5.desc:
Polkit-Qt is a library that lets developers use the Polkit API through
a nice Qt-styled API. It is mainly a wrapper around QAction and
QAbstractButton that lets you integrate those two component easily
with Polkit.

poppler.name: poppler
poppler.desc:
Poppler is a fork of the xpdf PDF viewer developed by Derek Noonburg
of Glyph and Cog, LLC.  It provides PDF rendering functionality as a
shared library, and uses modern components from Freedesktop.org such as
fontconfig and cairo to take advantage of modern UNIX desktops.

poppler-glib.name: poppler-glib
poppler-glib.desc:
Poppler is a fork of the xpdf PDF viewer developed by Derek Noonburg
of Glyph and Cog, LLC.  It provides PDF rendering functionality as a
shared library, and uses modern components from Freedesktop.org such as
fontconfig and cairo to take advantage of modern UNIX desktops.

poppler-qt5.name: poppler-qt5
poppler-qt5.desc:
Poppler is a fork of the xpdf PDF viewer developed by Derek Noonburg
of Glyph and Cog, LLC.  It provides PDF rendering functionality as a
shared library, and uses modern components from Freedesktop.org such as
fontconfig and cairo to take advantage of modern UNIX desktops.

popt.name: popt
popt.comment: Getopt(3) like library with a number of enhancements, from Redhat
popt.desc:
This is the popt command line option parsing library. While it is similar
to getopt(3), it contains a number of enhancements, including:

        1) popt is fully reentrant
        2) popt can parse arbitrary argv[] style arrays while
           getopt(2) makes this quite difficult
        3) popt allows users to alias command line arguments
        4) popt provides convenience functions for parsing strings
           into argv[] style arrays

postgresql13-client.name: postgresql13-client
postgresql13-client.desc:
PostgreSQL is a sophisticated Object-Relational DBMS, supporting
almost all SQL constructs, including subselects, transactions, and
user-defined types and functions. It is the most advanced open-source
database available anywhere. Commercial Support is also available.

The original Postgres code was the effort of many graduate students,
undergraduate students, and staff programmers working under the direction of
Professor Michael Stonebraker at the University of California, Berkeley. In
1995, Andrew Yu and Jolly Chen took on the task of converting the DBMS query
language to SQL and created a new database system which came to known as
Postgres95. Many others contributed to the porting, testing, debugging and
enhancement of the Postgres95 code. As the code improved, and 1995 faded into
memory, PostgreSQL was born.

PostgreSQL development is presently being performed by a team of Internet
developers who are now responsible for all current and future development. The
development team coordinator is Marc G. Fournier (scrappy@PostgreSQL.ORG).
Support is available from the PostgreSQL developer/user community through the
support mailing list (questions@PostgreSQL.ORG).

PostgreSQL is free and the complete source is available.

postgresql-docs
  For all of the html documentation

p5-Pg
  A perl5 API for client access to PostgreSQL databases.

postgresql-tcltk 
  If you want tcl/tk client support.

postgresql-jdbc
  For Java JDBC support.

postgresql-odbc
  For client access from unix applications using ODBC as access
  method. Not needed to access unix PostgreSQL servers from Win32
  using ODBC. See below.

ruby-postgres, py-psycopg2
  For client access to PostgreSQL databases using the ruby & python
  languages.

postgresql-plperl, postgresql-pltcl & postgresql-plruby
  For using perl5, tcl & ruby as procedural languages.

postgresql-contrib
  Lots of contributed utilities, postgresql functions and
  datatypes. There you find pg_standby, pgcrypto and many other cool
  things.

etc...

almost all SQL constructs, including subselects, transactions, and

messages.message:
For procedural languages and postgresql functions, please note that
you might have to update them when updating the server.

If you have many tables and many clients running, consider raising
kern.maxfiles using sysctl(8), or reconfigure your kernel
appropriately.

The port is set up to use autovacuum for new databases, but you might
also want to vacuum and perhaps backup your database regularly. There
is a periodic script, /usr/local/etc/periodic/daily/502.pgsql, that
you may find useful. You can use it to backup and perform vacuum on all
databases nightly. Per default, it performs `vacuum analyze'. See the
script for instructions. For autovacuum settings, please review
~postgres/data/postgresql.conf.

If you plan to access your PostgreSQL server using ODBC, please
consider running the SQL script /usr/local/share/postgresql/odbc.sql
to get the functions required for ODBC compliance.

Please note that if you use the rc script,
/usr/local/etc/rc.d/postgresql, to initialize the database, unicode
(UTF-8) will be used to store character data by default.  Set
postgresql_initdb_flags or use login.conf settings described below to
alter this behaviour. See the start rc script for more info.

To set limits, environment stuff like locale and collation and other
things, you can set up a class in /etc/login.conf before initializing
the database. Add something similar to this to /etc/login.conf:
---
postgres:\
	:lang=en_US.UTF-8:\
	:setenv=LC_COLLATE=C:\
	:tc=default:
---
and run `cap_mkdb /etc/login.conf'.
Then add 'postgresql_login_class="postgres"' to /etc/rc.conf, or
set it as the postgres user's login class in /etc/passwd.

======================================================================

To use PostgreSQL, enable it in rc.conf using

  sysrc postgresql_enable=yes

To initialize the database, run

  service postgresql initdb

You can then start PostgreSQL by running:

  service postgresql start

For postmaster settings, see ~postgres/data/postgresql.conf

NB. FreeBSD's PostgreSQL port logs to syslog by default
    See ~postgres/data/postgresql.conf for more info

NB. If you're not using a checksumming filesystem like ZFS, you might
    wish to enable data checksumming. It can be enabled during
    the initdb phase, by adding the "--data-checksums" flag to
    the postgresql_initdb_flags rcvar. Otherwise you can enable it later by
    pg_checksums.  Check the initdb(1) manpage for more info
    and make sure you understand the performance implications.

======================================================================
